{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "There is a natural way to regard product vectors in the string-net subspace H C 1 as string diagrams on Σ C 1.",
    "For a given string-net labelling l ∈ L SN (C), considerunit vectors f v ∈ H v (l) for all v ∈ C 0.",
    "Recall that f v is a morphism in C. Denoting f = (f v) v∈C 0, we define ϕ f = v∈C 0 f v ∈ H C (l).",
    "By construction, ϕ f belongs to the string-net subspace H C 1, and H C 1 is spanned by such product vectors.",
    "We define the corresponding string diagram x f on Σ C 1 whose graph is the intersection of the graph of Z 2 with the surface Σ C 1 (with edges directed towards the top right), which has edges labelled according to l, and vertices v ∈ C 0 labelled by the morphisms f v. We define π C 1:H C 1 → A(Σ C 1) by π C 1 (ϕ f) = [x f] Σ C 1,(21)where we interpret the string diagram x f as a string diagram on Σ C 1.The following lemma extends Lemma 5.3 of [36] to include surfaces with boundary."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "We define the corresponding string diagram x f on Σ C 1 whose graph is the intersection of the graph of Z 2 with the surface Σ C 1 (with edges directed towards the top right), which has edges labelled according to l, and vertices v ∈ C 0 labelled by the morphisms f v. We define π C 1:H C 1 → A(Σ C 1) by π C 1 (ϕ f) = [x f] Σ C 1,(21)where we interpret the string diagram x f as a string diagram on Σ C 1.The following lemma extends Lemma 5.3 of [36] to include surfaces with boundary."
